*Application class

  No changes to the standard Spring Boot application class are needed:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestfunction/SpringRestFunctionApplication.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*The YAML pipeline

  The entire pipeline for <<<POST /order>>> lives in one file:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/order.POST.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  Reading the file top-to-bottom is reading the specification.  Each entry is a named step.  The
  <<<class>>> key names the Java class that implements it.  <<<outputs>>> maps a conditional branch
  name to its target step.  <<<next>>> names the unconditional continuation.

  None of the three Java classes imports or references the others.  Changing the pipeline — adding a
  logging step, reordering, bypassing a step in staging — is a YAML edit with no Java changes.



*Step 1 — validate: conditional routing with <<<@Flow>>>

  The <<<validate>>> step is the entry point.  It receives the request body and decides whether to
  proceed or short-circuit.  The conditional branch is expressed as a custom functional interface
  annotated with {{{/apidocs/net/officefloor/plugin/section/clazz/Flow.html}@Flow}}:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestfunction/ValidateOrderLogic.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  <<<@Flow("valid")>>> tells OfficeFloor that calling <<<validFlow.flow(order)>>> routes execution
  to whatever step is mapped to <<<valid>>> in the YAML — here, <<<price>>>.  The <<<OrderRequest>>>
  passed to <<<flow()>>> is automatically available as a
  {{{/apidocs/net/officefloor/plugin/section/clazz/Parameter.html}@Parameter}} in the receiving step.

  When the request is invalid, <<<response.send(...)>>> is called directly and the <<<price>>> and
  <<<save>>> steps are never invoked for that request.



*Step 2 — price: sequential step with a typed return value

  The <<<price>>> step receives the validated <<<OrderRequest>>> as a <<<@Parameter>>> and uses a
  Spring <<<PricingService>>> to calculate the total.  The return value becomes the <<<@Parameter>>>
  for the next step:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestfunction/CalculatePricingLogic.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  Returning a value and using <<<next>>> in the YAML is the lightweight alternative to <<<@Flow>>>
  when there is no branching.  The returned <<<PricedOrder>>> is a plain data carrier — it holds
  exactly the information the next step needs, nothing more.



*Step 3 — save: Spring service and response

  The <<<save>>> step receives the <<<PricedOrder>>>, delegates persistence to a Spring
  <<<OrderService>>>, and writes the final response:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestfunction/SaveOrderLogic.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}



