*Testing

  Each step is a plain Java class — unit-testable without any framework by simply instantiating it
  and calling the method.  Integration tests use the standard Spring Boot <<<MockMvc>>> approach:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/test/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestfunction/SpringRestFunctionHttpServerTest.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  <<<validOrderFlowsThroughPipeline>>> confirms the full pipeline ran: the order ID is assigned, the
  product and quantity are echoed, and the total is the expected price.  <<<invalidOrderStopsAtValidation>>>
  confirms the short-circuit: <<<orderId>>> is null (no order was created) and <<<total>>> is zero
  (the pricing step never ran).



*What you have now

  After completing this tutorial you can:

   * Declare a multi-step request pipeline as a single YAML file

   * Use <<<@Flow>>> with a custom functional interface for conditional branching

   * Use method return values and <<<next>>> for sequential continuation

   * Pass typed data between steps via <<<@Parameter>>>

   * Inject Spring beans into any step without touching the others

  The pipeline is the YAML.  The Java classes are independent units.  Adding, reordering, or removing
  a step is a YAML change only.



